==English==

===Etymology===
From [[w:Old English language|Old English]][[category:Old English derivations]] [[Gypcyan]], [[w:French language|French]][[category:French derivations]] [[gyptien]] (meaning [[Egyptian]], [[gypsy]]), from [[w:Latin|Latin]][[Category:Latin derivations]] [[Aegyptius]]. See [[Egyptian]]. 

===Noun===
{{en-noun|gypsy|gypsies}}
# A member of the [[Roma]]. This term is considered pejorative by the Roma themselves.
# (Webster) One of a vagabond race, whose tribes, coming originally from India, entered Europe in 14th or 15th century, and are now scattered over Turkey, Russia, Hungary, Spain, England, etc., living by theft, fortune telling, horsejockeying, tinkering, etc. Cf. Bohemian, Romany. 
#:''Like a right '''gypsy'', hath, at fast and loose, Beguiled me to the very heart of loss.'' [[w:Shakespeare|Shakespeare]][[Category:Shakespeare Quotes]]
# hence, any [[itinerant]] person or any person or group suspected of making a living from dishonest practices or theft etc.
#:''If anyone questions them, they'll [[fold up]] faster than a '''gypsy''' roofing [[company]].''

